1558":"1558","1503":"1503","1502":"1502","1485":"1485","1570":"1570","about 1485":"about 1485","1549":"1549","Abt 1503":"about 1503","Horsham, Sussex, England":"Horsham, Sussex, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hackney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Hackney in Greater London, named from an Old English personal name <i>Haca</i> (genitive <i>Hacan</i>) + <i>ēg</i> ‘island, dry ground in marshland’.","perhaps from Middle English <i>hakenei</i> (Old French <i>haquenée</i>), an ambling horse or mare, especially one considered suitable for women to ride; perhaps therefore a metonymic occupational name for a breeder or keeper of such horses and short for <i>Hakeneyman</i>. This surname has also been found in Scotland since medieval times."],"variants":[{"name":"Oakley","meanings":["English (mainly West Midlands): habitational name from any of numerous places called Oakley, Oakle, or Oakleigh, in Bedfordshire, Essex, Gloucestershire, Hampshire, Kent, Somerset, Suffolk, or Wiltshire. The placenames derive from Old English <i>āc</i> ‘oak’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘open woodland’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":64,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":73,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705205,"age":84,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Thomas Hackney was born about 1485, in Sussex, England. She had at least 1 daughter with Thomas Hackney."},"et":{"about 1485–":"umbes 1485–Surnud","1485–1502":"1485–1502","1503–1570":"1503–1570","1485–Female":"1485–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1503":"1503","1502":"1502","1485":"1485","1570":"1570","about 1485":"umbes 1485","1549":"1549","Abt 1503":"umbes 1503","Horsham, Sussex, England":"Horsham, Sussex, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fi":{"about 1485–":"noin 1485–Kuollut","1485–1502":"1485–1502","1503–1570":"1503–1570","1485–Female":"1485–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1503":"1503","1502":"1502","1485":"1485","1570":"1570","about 1485":"noin 1485","1549":"1549","Abt 1503":"noin 1503","Horsham, Sussex, England":"Horsham, Sussex, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fr":{"about 1485–":"environ 1485–Décédée","1485–1502":"1485–1502","1503–1570":"1503–1570","1485–Female":"1485–Décédée","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1503":"1503","1502":"1502","1485":"1485","1570":"1570","abo